SILVER SCURF, POTATO - USA: INCREASE
************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 5 Mar 2018, 8:00 AM
Source: Agweek [edited]
http://www.agweek.com/business/agriculture/4411406-silver-scurf-great-name-bad-spuds


"I'm getting more questions about silver scurf at harvest," said Andy Robinson, North Dakota State and Minnesota Universities. Potato growers see the disease as a growing threat. Amanda Gevens, University of Wisconsin, also is seeing more silver scurf, a common potato disease found in all major production areas of the United States.

Efforts to combat silver scurf are complicated by its close resemblance to black dot, another crop disease. "Sometimes you can't tell them apart," [she said]. One important difference: silver scurf is tied to infected seed, while black dot is more of a soil/field debris issue. No commercial cultivars resistant to silver scurf are available yet, though work to develop them is underway.

Use of uninfected seed, which can be hard to get, helps to control the disease, as does early harvest and chemical use. Storage conditions also influence the extent of silver scurf in affected potatoes.

[Byline: Jonathan Knutson]

